description: Exploit and remediate session management exposures. A Session Fixation occurs when authenticating users without invalidating any existing session identifier. When terminating users session, if this is performed by setting the Cookie to a new value while the server-side state remains active, the old session could be reused.
topics: Session Fixation, Session Not Invalidated Upon Logout
title: Broken Session Management
trophyDescription: The candidate can remediate simple Session Management exposures in Java.

infoList.title: Starting the exercise
infoList.description: When starting the exercise you will be presented with an Ubuntu desktop. Wait for Eclipse IDE and Firefox to launch.

infoList.title: Eclipse
infoList.description: Switch to Eclipse, click on the "Servers" tab, then click on "Start the Server" to launch the application server.

infoList.title: Firefox
infoList.description: Switch to Firefox, browse to: http://www.vulnerableapp.com:8050 . Login to the Vulnerable Application using the following credentials: user / password

infoList.title: Finishing the exercise
infoList.description: When you have completed the exercise, browse to Running Exercises" and click on "Mark Completed". Provisional results will be available in the "History" tab.

infoList.title: Troubleshooting
infoList.description: Restore source code: if you accidentally break the app's functionality, you can reset the app to the original source code using the shell script at: /home/rtf/Desktop/RTF/restoreSource.sh

flagList.instructions: Get a valid session identifier and trick a victim into clicking on a malicious link to steal their session. Reference step-by-step instructions in the Exercise's reference document.
Remediate the exposure by editing the class actions.LoginAction.

hint.text: Invalidate the current session and generate a new session upon successful authentication.
